{"text": "What is different compared to Ubisoft's Rainbow Six: Siege * new randomized maps each week -> there will no be popularly known spots like in Siege maps * no scout drones during attack * you play three rounds in one side  ^ your side has fixed inventory during those rounds, meaning that you have to spare equipment for all three rounds. * no prone, only crouch What Ubisoft's Rainbow Six: Siege has that Due Process  : - cosmetic skins lootboxes - Battle pass - Requirement of Uplay - Season pass that costs 30 bucks to get eight new operators in a year. I don't know about you but those two last \"don't haves\" are very easy way to convince me play this rather than R6: Siege. More casual than Squad but more teamwork & mic-communication focused than your regular Call Of Duty or Battlefield game.", "appid": "753650", "steamid": "profiles/76561198271105938", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": "1", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1598184000.0}
{"text": "PERSPECTIVE REVIEW This game is a little too short. This is a great game to let the little nieces and nephews play. As far as kids go, I think a game like this occasionally teaches them to think things through and have a \"big picture\" sort of spacial awareness. Because the answer to certain levels are so clear, it can sometimes take a while to realize it. Unless you're really bad at puzzles, this game will be very short (around 2 to 6 hours, maybe). There's around 70 to 80 levels - almost double the original Snakebird, but many of them are pretty much just movement exercises. (Fun movement exercises, but still just an exercise in moving from a simple start to a simple finish.) Maybe I'm being greedy but I feel like the island should be bigger, or maybe a second island. For $8, I expect more playtime out of a game - even if that playtime consists of extremely simple tasks or puzzles. Now, you pair this with the original Snakebird & total the pricing and I feel like I got more than my money's worth out of the lot (even if I'd not bought them on sale) but the original Snakebird already suffices in doing that for me, on its own. Completion of levels in the original Snakebird also feels more rewarding, due to the need to work for it.  I understand that this game is easier (especially if you played the original first) however, I do still have a minimum expectation of a certain amount of minimum playtime per dollar. Overall, I can overlook the issues I have with this game being both easy & short (I don't mind easy when it both occupies my time sufficiently and manages to be engaging or entertaining) because of my strong love of Snakebird. Truly, I find this to be one of the most child-friendly and entertaining puzzle series that I have ever played in my life. I would also, very muchly like to see how my sister or nephew perform in this game - I probably won't get to see that but it's nice to have it around, just in case. I know that the \"primer\" section of my review isn't very flattering but I think this is the most important stuff for you to know before getting the game. Ultimately, I find this game to be well-designed, well-balanced, and highly enjoyable - just too short. I would recommend it to anyone that struggles with puzzles or loves fun colorful things, though. (Or is a big fan of Snakebird).  I'm less inclined to tell you to wait for a sale with the original Snakebird and more inclined to recommend sale prices for Primer but I think someone who struggles with puzzles more might feel the opposite about which one has the better price tag. (for those who have to concern themselves with budgets) Now, all that said, it is clear that they put a fairly sizable amount of work into Primer. Creating friendlier levels, testing them, and then putting them in an order that made the most sense for stringing you along for a comfortable ride that teaches you what you need to know to progress.  However, it still will do little to teach you if you do not actively THINK about what you need to do - perhaps even moreso than the original Snakebird, as it's very easy to complete levels through trial and error in Snakebird Primer. On the other hand, because of how many times it makes you do the same simple tasks in different ways, with the variety of levels that it presents to you, you are much more likely to develop muscle memory and learn how to get around sub-conciously, even if you aren't actively thinking about it. There's no level editor, or randomly generated maps, or anything, so if you're looking for a game that you can play for the rest of your life, this isn't it - but if you're looking for a cute, and fun, relaxing...ish, unique experience that should test your mind a little bit, for a short while, this is it.", "appid": "1014140", "steamid": "profiles/76561198120041629", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": 0, "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1567857600.0}
