{"text": "Ok so I DID NOT play the original Witcher game and I found that it really didn't affect my overall enjoyment and understanding of the game.  My god has this game not story and narrative overload! There is a lot of lore and backstory to the world and the characters. From side characters like Triss, Zoltan and Roache, you meet so many characters with interesting stories and lore behind them that you can't help but make sure you know every detail about their lives! For the first time in ages in a video game, I wanted the conversations to keep going (which, to me, is an outstanding feat). You play as Geralt of Rivia again; a witcher who is framed for the assassination of a king as is on a quest to rid his name of false accusations. At first, seems like a pretty straight forward story but it soon takes many different side stories, background quests and just overall outstanding lore. I don't want to get too much more into the story but trust me; it's detailed! My only real complaint about the story is sometimes it can get a little hard to follow and the characters you meet are drip-feeded quite quickly (it is a much shorter game after all, just look at my playtime) however a quick read of the detailed glossary always made sure I knew what was going on and why. There seems to be only one really major decision during act 1 of the game that truly affects the game but then again, I cannot judge too much as I haven't played through twice (which apparently is the way to play it which can increase play time by about another 30-40 hours).  I had strongly mixed feelings about this gameplay system. One thing that is   noticeable is the restricted movement system. To be honest, it is not that bad but it can kind of feel generic and weird at times (seeing as you can't jump either). Exploration is encouraged with plenty of side quests to be discovered and areas to explore and secrets to discover. Inventory management is far from perfect but it's efficient enough that I didn't get   frustrated at it. Combat is definately interesting and a mixed bag. At first, it feels so restrictive and clunky with awkward aiming and slow casted spells. In fact, the control scheme for me on a mouse and keyboard got so irritating that I ended up using a controller. However once you level up Geralt and his abilities the combat becomes much more fun and engaging but still not fluent. As you journey around the zones you'll pick up crafting items to help craft oils and other alchemy items. Now this might sound tedious  its quite fun and rewarding and also really neccessary. Overall, the fighting is not perfect but still quite fun and I enjoyed most of the fights (minus some annoying boss fights). There is also plenty of items to craft too (armour, swords, etc). My god this game is still beautiful after how many years?! The lighting and detail in the areas is an absolute joy to observe! I am playing this on high and ultra settings (FXAA) at a constant 75 FPS and it is still an absolute joy to soak in all the details and colour. The character models and items look authentic too however, they do suffer from odd animations during conversations (but this isn't a huge deal breaker0. The voice acting is overall pretty well done with some convincing performances.  Overall the Witcher 2 is one of my all time favourite RPG's. Deep crafting, combat, skills and story kept me coming back week after week. The only thing that got me to stop playing was that I moved to the Witcher 3 (review coming soon)! I highly reccommend this 'forgotten' gem as it truly is a master piece in game design.", "appid": "20920", "steamid": "profiles/76561198058876618", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": 0, "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1460030400.0}
