{"text": "Interesting game in the old-school turn based dungeon crawler style. The artwork and voice acting are excellent. Unfortunately the story seems rather generic so far, hero follows a dream to their destiny, fighting to rid the world of a cursed king, saving damsels in distress along the way. Don't know how much more interesting it gets after the demo's first quest, but the only thing that saves it at the start is the voice work.  The gameplay seems somewhat shallow, at least at the beginning. You start with 2 abilities that are on cooldown, then you just spam an energy-generator + defensive ability on its cooldown, and the rest of the time spam your basic melee or ranged attack. Rinse, repeat, and repeat some more.  I like the variable difficulty settings, allowing me to do something like turning the combat difficulty up while leaving the minimap and quest markers on. Unfortunately while this, permadeath option, and the different classes suggest doing multiple runs, it can be a little tedious as skipping dialogue takes multiple keys and there's sometimes multiple chats to skip through, or unskippable short \"cutscenes.\" An option to skip introductory story would be great for subsequent runs. The gamepad controller support also needs work. It seems like it keeps wanting to swap back to mouse+keyboard, to the point where it even became impossible for me to equip items with my gamepad. Eventually I just gave up and played the game with M+KB.. which is fine, but I would have liked the option to use the gamepad, especially if it's listed as a feature in store page.  Exploration was good enough, though it could have been better. Some slightly out of the way items to collect, some neat little secrets like torches opening hidden doors or translucent walls you can walk through. Unfortunately the early puzzles just felt tedious, too easy to be considered a challenged but still there to slightly inconvenience you. The game world itself is also kind of annoying, I ended up finding it to be more efficient to just navigate via the minimap. Others may enjoy having to memorize the dungeon layout, but I sure wouldn't. Overall a pleasant experience. I enjoyed my time with the demo, doing a complete ranger run at first, then a complete mage run, and started a warrior just to get a taste of how different the combat would be. Overall the classes more or less play the same, just with slightly different abilities and different primary stats. The game isn't my favorite ever truth be told, but it was fun enough I may eventually buy it on sale and play through the whole thing.", "appid": "1269000", "steamid": "profiles/76561198087330162", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": 0, "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1584619200.0}
