{"text": "Game version: Build 10   Fun and varied with a surprising amount of depth. At its heart it's a wave-based shooter. Adventure mode has you take on waves of enemies before fighting a boss and moving onto the next area. Dungeon mode is less hectic and does away with the waves, instead having you descend random dungeon levels (with destructible walls!) until you get down to the boss. Enemies get tougher as you progress, but you level up along the way and can assign earned skill points to make yourself stronger, tougher, and faster as you see fit. You also collect gold which is spent between waves at the shop on new weapons or ammo and supplies. After you die the game tallies up the gold you collected and adds it to a running total, which you can use to permanently upgrade your character's starting stats or weapons so you'll do better next time. The waves of enemies are massive, which makes it all the more satisfying when you tear through them en-masse with a powerful special weapon or a decked out shotgun or grenade launcher. A really nice touch is that each area has its own matching set of enemies (e.g. jellyfish in the underwater area). Further switching things up, the bosses have unique attacks with bullet hell like patterns instead of simply being an oversized enemy. Where things get really get interesting is its weapon system. There's tons of disposable special weapons you can find as drops and you'll never know quite what they'll do until you try them. Your mainstays are five basics weapon types (pistol / SMG / shotgun / rifle / grenade launcher), and those each have three mod slots and an artifact slot (except the pistol). As you plow down enemies you'll find mods that range from simple accuracy/damage/fire rate boosts to ones that affect the projectiles themselves, like \"homing\" which makes them gravitate towards enemies. It felt like I was cheating when I first used a spread mod on the grenade launcher to make it 3 grenades per shot, but as enemies got harder and soaked more damage it became important to conserve ammunition by finding mod combinations that made each weapon as effective as possible. The SMG was my least favorite because it didn't do much damage per shot and large hoards seemed to eat its ammo like candy, but when modded with damage boosts it became extremely effective at taking down bosses quickly through sheer DPS. I happily played multiple rounds of Adventure mode, experimenting with weapon mods without giving magical attacks much of a chance. Yep, magic is a thing too. Also pets. Did I mention there's a surprising amount of depth? But it's not overwhelming, and you don't have to master every mechanic to have fun. Besides it being hard to keep track of enemy projectiles when using a weapon that floods the screen (large projectile mods especially), my only real complaint is that I couldn't enjoy the soundtrack much at all. Some tracks have a nice chiptune sound (FamiTracker?) but rather jarringly others are straight up MIDI. Musical taste is entirely subjective of course, but little evoked any sort of emotion from me. The main menu gets me pumped, the little jingle when defeating a boss makes me feel accomplished, the pet sanctuary music fittingly makes me picture a peaceful utopia, but in-between most of the tracks just feel like background music.", "appid": "384500", "steamid": "profiles/76561198017975643", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": "2", "votes_funny": "1", "early_access": true, "tstamp_created": 1464609600.0}
