{"text": "A premissa de Friday the 13th: The Game Ã© bem simples, oito jogadores entram em uma partida e um deles Ã© sorteado para ser o icÃ´nico assassino da mÃ¡scara de hÃ³quei. O objetivo dos demais passa a ser o de sobreviver a qualquer custo, seja fugindo ou se escondendo e evitando Jason atÃ© o tempo de partida se esgotar. Parece simplista demais mas funciona de uma forma muito satisfatÃ³ria, especialmente quando se trata de trabalhar em equipe para conseguir as partes necessÃ¡rias, seja para fazer um carro funcionar ou para fazer um simples telefonema para a polÃ­cia local. Os mapas sÃ£o variados e muito bem construÃ­dos, a ambientaÃ§Ã£o Ã© magnÃ­fica e os grÃ¡ficos sÃ£o muito bons. Quanto a bugs posso citar a renderizaÃ§Ã£o do jogo, que muitas das vezes acaba ocasionando um problema de texturas borradas, mas nada que tire o brilho do jogo pois estes bugs duram segundinhos. Jogar de Jason Ã© super gratificante e ao mesmo tempo desafiador, pois dependendo da habilidade dos jogadores vocÃª terÃ¡ de prestar atenÃ§Ã£o nas aÃ§Ãµes dos mesmos, isto Ã©, impedi-los de realizar reparos nos carros/barcos e de fazer telefonemas a polÃ­cia. Tudo isso enquanto vocÃª os caÃ§a. Definitivamente vale o preÃ§o, atÃ© mesmo fora de promoÃ§Ã£o. Se Terror + SobrevivÃªncia for a sua praia entÃ£o estÃ¡ mais do que recomendado.", "appid": "438740", "steamid": "profiles/76561198207364875", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": "12", "votes_funny": "5", "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1592827200.0}
{"text": "I was really impressed with Carrion right from the start.  The monster itself gave me vibes of The Thing and Stranger Things, which is definitely a good thing! Not often do you get to play as a monster, such a concept is an intriguing one. Instead of being part of a group of scientists trying desperately to survive against impossible odds, youâ€™re the one killing all the humans in an attempt to escape a research facility. Itâ€™s a bloody, intense roller coaster that gets better and better as you make your way towards the satisfying conclusion. The whole game isnâ€™t just a murder spree, though. Youâ€™ll come across various puzzles, as well. These conundrums will require your extraterrestrial to deposit its biomass into pools of water and shrink in size. Why would you want to become smaller? Well, certain abilities are tied to the three tiers of proportions that make up the alien. The smallest one allows you to shoot webbing and become invisible, the medium variant has the capacity to charge through certain obstacles, and the largest provides an impenetrable shield for a short period of time. Knowing when to grow or shrink is key to finishing your journey. The only real issue that Carrion has is that it can be difficult to know where to go next sometimes. There are no waypoints or objectives of any sort, so in the later parts it can be difficult to navigate. This becomes even more true when players have to travel back through earlier areas to find ways to progress. There are times when the player may find themselves wandering aimlessly or taking a wrong turn and not remembering how to return. The best advice is that players should try to stick to the beaten path unless they remember exactly how to get back. Carrion isn't a very long game, and most gamers will probably be able to beat it in about half a dozen hours. It is very much worth every single second though. Playing as a horrific monster destroying everything in its path is a lot of fun, and it never gets old to rip pesky humans and drones to pieces. Carrion goes hard and fast, but never overstays its welcome.", "appid": "953490", "steamid": "profiles/76561197970993315", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": "1", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1596715200.0}
