{"text": "Notwithstanding Darksiders III, the previous work of Gunfire Games which is a quite terrible game, I had very high hopes for Remnant. Unfortunately, Remnant also turned out to be a huge letdown as the developers don't seem to have learned from their mistakes with Darksiders III. This is yet another game that tries to blindly follow in the footsteps of Dark Souls without even realizing what makes those games such masterpieces. It delivers challenge and difficulty for sure but falls short of expectations in almost every other aspect. Difficulty is not a magic bullet that can make any game great, I wish more developers understood this. Thankfully, Remnant is miles ahead of Lords of the Fallen & Immortal Unchained which isn't really saying much, since both of those games are utter garbage. I could probably say I've enjoyed Remnant more than The Surge as well but then again, I still think The Surge is also a terrible video game. So far, the Soulslike genre has bred far more blind copycats and failed experiments than high-quality and enjoyable experiences, at least for me personally. Story and gameplay often make or break a game for me, neither of which is any good in Remnant. Story telling goes straight off the rails right from the get-go with the starting cutscene being one of the worst I have ever seen in any video game (Did they just rip the intro off Monster Hunter World?!!). It only gets worse from there, if that were even possible, as the dialog feels like it's been written by a group of children which is rather peculiar because the quality of writing in the journals is actually quite decent. Gameplay isn't much better as the mind-boggling level scaling smothers any sense of progression and ruins any chance of redemption. I wish I could say your character controls like a tank, but it actually controls more like a drunk cripple. Because Vaulting and Dodging are bound to the same button, you are very likely to get killed close to cover (especially in boss battles) when your character decides to vault into an attack or take cover instead of dodging away from it. The Stamina system feels badly thought-out and is more of an annoyance than anything. Overall, it really is NOT enjoyable at all, at least it wasn't for me... So to end this review on a slightly positive note, the artwork and graphic design are breathtaking, so are the music and soundtrack. The voice acting is surprisingly well-done considering how terrible the actual dialog is, but the scarcity of it leaves a great deal to be desired. - High replay value - Breathtaking art design - Serviceable voice acting - Decent writing (only for journals) - Astounding soundtrack and music - Incredible sound effects and audio - Extremely challenging - Quantity over quality (lots of content) - Awful story - Abysmal dialog - Horrible netcode - Tedious gameplay - Twitchy animations - Terrible level design - Unresponsive controls - Lack of weapon variety - Lackluster RPG elements - Poor balance due to enemy Level Scaling  6/10 - Mediocre Remnant: From the Ashes is a mediocre game at best that is held down by poor gameplay design, deplorable story telling with laughable dialog and janky controls that barely feel functional. Ultimately, I cannot recommend this game to anyone but the most hardcore fans of the Soulslike genre that are aching for ANY experience that feels even remotely similar (and challenging).", "appid": "617290", "steamid": "profiles/76561197963259080", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "28", "votes_funny": "9", "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1566216000.0}
