{"text": "I tried. I really did. The technical issues make a lackluster experience worse. Presumably, given how many other game references the first Darksiders seemed to pull from, the second one must have been inspired by what was popular at the time. I'm just spit-balling, but   was pretty popular and only was released 3 years prior. Mayhaps? You get a ton of loot in this game. But my main contention is that it adds very little to the game and ends up being a nuisance needing to constantly look if you're using your best gear. There is no way to easily sort it either â€” at least not that I found. The first Darksiders handled weaponry really well while still giving you options and increasing its damage the more you used them. You weren't constantly perusing your   of garbage loot. Those weapons and gear in the first game also aided you in solving puzzles. Comparing gear really bogs you down when you're trying to do puzzles in a Zelda style dungeon. However, Death is a a lot more spry than War. (You play as Death in this, War's brother. Another horseman of the apocalypse.) Death is so much more spry that most of the puzzles involve   style environment puzzles. But to a much lesser degree than that. It seemed as though I just spent a lot of time looking for what wall I was supposed to be running on. That became the crux of the puzzle.  As I mentioned, the FOV of this game really hurts it. Small areas filled with 5 or 6 enemies where half of them are behind you off screen. More often than not I was dodging before my combo was over simply to avoid getting hit by imagined attacks of would-be purveyors of aggression. The other times I'd just get hit. This brings me to my next point, many of the enemies are damage sponges while Death is rather fragile. At least early on, I'm sure that changes later with better loot and leveling.  You're able to level into other skills such as summoning ghouls that surround you and fight for you, teleporting scythe attacks that [potentially] start enemies on fire should you level that way. I found these things only mitigated my growing agitation. I also found that the combos that Death is capable of much less interesting than that of War's. You still had delayed input combos mixed with air juggling but Death is so fast with his dual scythes, the game compensates by the scythes being a tad underpowered. So I ended up using the larger, slower weapons like the hammers, maces and big scythes. However, I found the combos for those also disappointing. It very much felt like I was doing crowd control more than fighting. Having recently just played Darksiders 1, I miss having that combat. Vulgrim is back, though he longer sells moves. He now sells loot boxes! Sorry,   These are bought with in-game currency but it's still annoying to deal with so much loot when it adds no real value.  Death also has a bird in addition to his horse [named Despair]. This bird, named Dust, reminds me a bit of \" \" on PS2. It flies around and tells you vaguely where the main objective is. Although, it's really probably more â€œNaviâ€-esque as it doesn't scout like the bird from Mark of Kri did. The world is even more open than before, the problem is that it's giant, filled with enemies and little else. It does look nice, though. For instance: The main enemy of this game   â€œcorruptionâ€ itself. The idea of this exaggerated manifestation of  human frailty literally corrupting the world is interesting. Especially as â€œDeathâ€ as its harbinger. Suggesting that   â€” as in, life itself requires corruption to exist for balance. But I'm not much for poetry.  Death also has some really cool animations for opening doors and chests. He has these ethereal hands that appear around him. He gently caresses the front of the object and these inter-dimensional hands rip the chest apart. It gives Death this other worldly feel. I just wish I wanted to be in that world. Darksiders 1 review  .", "appid": "388410", "steamid": "profiles/76561198064850410", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "13", "votes_funny": "3", "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1604750400.0}
