{"text": "The game is, like the previous HOI entries, a grand strategy game where you control a country from the start of the build up to WWII onwards. The game itself is good with all the complexity you would expect from Paradox grand strategy title. The interface is usable and fairly logical and clear, the graphics serve their purpose as does the sound. The only real issues with the game itself are a rather feeble AI which is easily exploited if you have the mind set to do it as well as quite a few stability issues (a common theme of all Paradox games I have come across to date) Where it really falls down is Paradoxâ€™s insistence on releasing core elements, or changing said elements, with paid for DLC. A good example of this is La RÃ©sistance. Without any â€˜opt outâ€™ option a patch changed the core mechanic of resistance in occupied countries and the use of spies. If you didnâ€™t pay for the related DLC  you were unable to use some features meant to control the system. Further compounding this is the new system itself was an artificial brake to fix an existing game issue (the German steamroller problem). So in effect you have to pay extra or have a broken mechanic in game all because of an earlier broken mechanic of the game was supposedly fixed. Bad replaced by bad. If Paradox can get the stability issues sorted (not much chance if you look at the previous HOI releases) and stop the dodgy money grubbing DLC policy it may be worth looking at. As it is now I cant recommend it", "appid": "394360", "steamid": "profiles/76561198007850719", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "2", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1593259200.0}
