{"text": "approaches badness from so many directions that I am left scratching my head. It combines all the worst ingredients from the genres it's trying to imitate and it ends in a frenzy of recycled elements, from better games, that are disappointing to say the least.Â  Here we are again, one year later, with another playable chapter to Movie Games Lunarium's upcoming X-Rated adventure game  . While the first prologue struck an interesting balance between sex, time period and atmosphere (I loved the Victorian setting and the Giger inspired visuals of the alien world), the same cannot be said here. To be honest, I wasn't expecting much before playing the prologue to the main game, having never played  , and I figured I was pretty much going to get a porn game with limited horror/adventure puzzle elements, solely existing to titillate, where in reality I got the opposite which was refreshing because at the end of the day while I enjoy my sex in games as much as anyone else, I actually need more game to go with it.  undoes all the goodwill the prologue built up as it moves the setting to present day and introduces us to the new games insipid protagonist, a horny dude named Alan who is looking for kinky sex, who five minutes into the game had me wishing someone would just hammer his â™¥â™¥â™¥â™¥ and balls to a block with a set of rusty nails and we could be done with it. It's clear what   is going for and that is to showcase about a much gratuitous violence and depravity as is possible in its short running time (the complete opposite to the prologue which focused more on the adventure element).Â  The environment, an old abandoned theatre, is generic even going as far to populate the area with that scary old horror game trope - mannequins (newsflash devs this isn't scary, and neither was there a time when it ever was), as if this is supposed to inspire some sort of dread in the player when they see them (yawn!).  Puzzles this time around, if you can call them puzzles, make no sense in the given context and are weak to solve. The general feeling I got was that they got ham-fisted in because someone in the team had to remind everyone else that they were making a \"horror/adventure/puzzle game with porn and not simply just a torture porn game\".   goes out of its way this time around to disgust.Â  The game has also added combat, a woefully implemented melee system, that is horrendously clunky that feels like it came out of a game from the early 2000's. Movie Games Lunarium have some serious work on their hands making it anywhere near enjoyable come the full release.  most certainly had my interest piqued, but   has had the opposite effect. By the end of it I was, frankly, stupefied. To call it absurd would be missing the point, since any shred of credibility has been thrown overboard in this episode in favour of perverted sex and violence. The game clearly has ambitions to be a sort of \"Eyes Wide Shut\" psycho-sexual thriller mixed with horror elements from \"Alien\" (which I am all on-board for) but did it have to aim to be so lurid? If they push any further in this direction it may as well become a comedy.", "appid": "1401680", "steamid": "profiles/76561198021551803", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "44", "votes_funny": "3", "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1603195200.0}
