{"text": "I am not exactly sure why this game is rated as \"Very Positive\". I didn't find more than an hour of gameplay here. I finished the first campaign, which is just a tutorial. The majority of that time was spent zoomed out waiting to see if my side would win or if I would have to repeat the battle with different units. I tried a few workshop campaigns but not a single one worked. I would start the campaign and there would be no enemy units so I could not \"start\" the battle. Pros: 1. Made me laugh once or twice when units would \"explode\" all over the battlefield. Cons: 1. No real game here. The campaign is nothing but trial and error until you get the right combination of units to beat whatever force you face. 2. None of the workshop downloads worked: This is obviously my problem as many people enjoy the workshop. However, apparently it is not intuitive how to get the campaigns I downloaded to actually work. 3. Slideshow of 5 FPS or less with larger amount of units. I am using an I5 7600K, 2080GTX, and 16GB of RAM for comparison. 4. I was bored after about 30 minutes. I continued to play for 30 more to try some workshop stuff. 5. Sandbox is nothing more than placing down a bunch of units for each side and watching to see who wins. How is this fun? 200 archers VS 1 Leonardo tank? 30 Zues VS 30 Kings? How many times can you do that before it is mind numbing? All-in-all, I cannot see where the appeal of this game comes from. It seems to me it may be fun to WATCH someone play it that can put a humorous spin on the battle, but that's it. I felt the same way about BeamNG.Drive.", "appid": "508440", "steamid": "profiles/76561197993202153", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "4", "votes_funny": "4", "early_access": true, "tstamp_created": 1572177600.0}
