{"text": "Well this was underwhelming and disappointing. Not that I expected something outstanding, but the game looked quite enticing at first glance. It has excellent visuals and is a 18+ otome, which is so rare that attracts attention. After playing the game, I can say gorgeous visuals are the only thing it has going for it. I had more fun captioning and commenting my screenshots than actually playing it. Story is the weakest part, world building non-existent. Donâ€™t get me wrong, I didnâ€™t expect some deep elaborate story, but at least something more engaging. The plot is fairly simple, when you strip it down, but it looks convoluted by confusing and boring magic technobabble. Yes, thatâ€™s right, this game makes magic boring. I donâ€™t know if itâ€™s full of plot holes, probably. I was long dead from boredom to pay attention to such details. It is also repetitive. There is no variation in the two route story/plot wise. Everything happens in the same way, just with a different guy as a bystander. This is not the problem of translation. The language itself is easy to follow and more or less natural (to my ears). There are some grammatical errors but nothing that would make it hard to read. The problem is deeper, the writing itself. This visual novel attempts to incorporate adventure/puzzle gameplay into itâ€™s structure, which is interesting, I guess. It feels more like HOG in that aspect (although hidden object scenes are more challenging) You have a few scenes where you â€˜performâ€™ a ritual, but thatâ€™s actually just clicking on hotspots. You may or may not listen to her technobabble (thank god, ugh) So this puzzle gameplay is severely watered down and doesnâ€™t really make the game more engaging, only more buggy.   So ok, itâ€™s not a good story (or puzzle game), but who cares, itâ€™s a 18+ otome. Surely I can enjoy it as a trashy romance novel at least. I wish! When the story and especially world building are weak then characters donâ€™t have the ground to stand on resulting in pretty thin characterisation and consequently romance. Although Iâ€™ve known quite a few fictional works with so-so  stories but interesting and engaging characters. Thatâ€™s not the case here. I donâ€™t even have much to say about them. Generic western MC: likes to technobabble and info dump..........has nice bo*obs. Two love interests are supposed to be polar opposites. Shanrae, the Druid, the half-naked flowerboy is sort of naive, nice, young..........has a six-pack. Canâ€™t quite think of more. Heâ€™s definitely a more striking eye-candy, abs on display and all. Seth, the Necromancer, is more interesting, but very tropey. Heâ€™s confident, cocky, blunt. The most entertaining thing in the whole game are his drunken rants. Itâ€™s like the writer had limited access to personality clay and used it all on Seth, forgetting to leave some for Shanrae.  With a story and characters like these itâ€™s no wonder that romance suffers. Itâ€™s very rushed and unconvincing, thereâ€™s barely any tension. It follows the same pattern for both guys:  So ok, itâ€™s not a good story (or puzzle game) or romance, but who cares, it has sex, in otome. All those other things are just a setting, an excuse for smut anyway, right? Wrong! Iâ€™ve read way better smut in fanfiction. But ff has the benefit of already established characters and worlds, all of which are sorely lacking here. Here, the smut is mechanical, bland, unexciting, especially in Shanraeâ€™s route. Itâ€™s not even especially bad so that I can at least laugh (like in Dogenzaka games) Itâ€™s just..... Itâ€™s a bit better in Sethâ€™s route just because heâ€™s more interesting anyway and thereâ€™s some tension in the romantic scene building up to it. But then it just goes into SM territory out of the blue.  So ok, who cares (actually at this point, everyone), it looks absolutely gorgeous. Yes thatâ€™s right, visuals are top-notch, from backgrounds and attractive sprites to amazing cgs full of vibrant colours. Sprites are also moving and have animated faces, especially eyes. Although the latter can be quite hilarious in the way rolling eyes makes them look doll-like.  Seth especially was rolling his eyes so hard he probably saw his brain. Music is ok too with some memorable tracks and goes nicely with the visuals. Ok thatâ€™s enough for positives. Sadly! Thereâ€™s one more negative thing that can be a problem for a lot of people. The game is buggy. Maybe less than before, but I encountered unresponsive or laggy mouse click especially in puzzle scenes and after skipping. Also there were sometimes long black outs between scenes. Steam overlay doesnâ€™t work so you canâ€™t take screenshots through steam client. Achievements still donâ€™t work. Usually the lack of achievements and trading cards doesnâ€™t influence the way I rate the game. But here, thatâ€™s one more thing to add on the pile of things that should be working, but donâ€™t. Maybe if the game worked smoothly it would be easier for some to overlook other shortcomings, especially on a good discount. : there's 3   - visuals, music, Seth's drunken rants...ok and Shanraeâ€™s chest and abs (Iâ€™m feeling generous); and a lot of   with greater weight - story and plot, world building, characters, romance, smut, no achievements where they should be, no steam overlay, buggy. You do the math. Also that saying â€˜all flash no substanceâ€™ (which is often misused) can be correctly applied here. I know we are starved for good adult otome, but that doesnâ€™t mean we have to settle for poorly written romance and smut. This review and many like it are not here to discourage indie developers (I hope they donâ€™t have that power), but to show that we just want better.", "appid": "890500", "steamid": "profiles/76561198291108165", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "26", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1593777600.0}
