{"text": "Oh joy, War Thunder. There's so much that can be said about this game and almost none of it good. Just gonna skip the pleasantries and wit for this one because honestly, it's not worth the effort. Let's start off with the matchmaking system. It's broken. Period. War Thunder's matchmaking system is based off of a vehicles' Battle Rating (BR), which is normally supposed to match you up with vehicles no higher or lower than 1 - 1.5 from your highest BR with preference to your specific BR, except it doesn't. I can't count how many matches I've been in where my max vehicle BR is 5.7 and I end up getting matched with 7.7's. It wouldn't be such a noteworthy issue if it was a new system, but it's been like this for  . How is a P-51 supposed to cope with 50's era jets and radar guided Anti-Aircraft vehicles? How is it fair for WWII tanks with primitive ammo to go up against Cold-War era tanks with advanceed fin stabilized or SABOT rounds that have zero trajectory drop? Thus brings me to key issue #2. There's no clear-cut line separating WWII aircraft from Cold-War aircraft. If your BR is sufficient enough, you risk the matchmaking system putting your Me-262 against F-86 Sabres, MiG-17's, Hunters, etc. and your Maus up agains T-64's, AMX-30's, and on the off chance M1 Abrams'. There's literally zero balance here, WWII armor has no chance against the advanced ammunition of late-game vehicles and WWII jet fighters will have circles danced around them by late-game jets. Most WWII vehicles end up getting sniped from across the map not long after the game has started and well before they get the enemy in weapons range. It's utterly abhorrant how long this has been allowed to go on, Speaking of getting sniped, issue #3 on my list has to do with ballistics. The German Tiger I has a body that is essentially a rectangle with no armor sloping to deflect incoming shots. The 1 foot tall plate (by my eyeballing it) protecting the front of the tank sits at a 100 degree angle from the bottom plate it's welded to with a thickness of 10.2cm. The American M4A3E2 (76) W has a  2 - 3 foot high frontal plate (again, eyeballing it) with a thickness of 3.81 cm but sits at a 137 degree angle. The APCR shell of the M4 can penetrate an armor plate of 12.4cm at 1000m distance. How is it that the M4 cannot penetrate that 10.2cm plate in a face-to-face confrontation at only a hundred meters away? How can that same Tiger I not penetrate the M4's armor at the same distance? How is it that the 10.5cm gun of a Tiger II 10.5 can't penetrate the armor of a T-54 with armor-piercing rounds?  How can a Ferdinand's shell explode on the ground yet still have the shrapnel penetrate an M4A3E2, ricochet off the motor and kill *all* the crew? Answer: Gaijin doesn't care. Almost every single patch they put out to \"balance\" something breaks the entire system. One group of tanks always ends up incredibly hard to kill (as of this draft it's the Sherman Jumbo series) or destroys other tanks far too easy. The same goes for aircraft. Right now the Bf-109 series can out-turn an A6M Zero in Simulator Battles. Excuse me?! On what planet is a Bf-109 F-2 more manoeverable than an A6M2? It's a total mess, and it's a problem Gaijin simply doesn't seem to care enough to fix; again going on for *years*. Pay-to-win honestly doesn't exist. Are the Gaijin fanboys gone? Alright. It's totally pay-to-win. You can buy currency (Golden Eagles) for in-game content and services. One such service is the ability to apply convertible research points (which you earn by the truck-load) to whatever vehicles you choose, effectively skipping   of dedicated gameplay and blasting through the tech tree. I checked this feature out to see if there was some sort of limit as to how much/how far you can research. There isn't one. I blasted my way from the American tier I P-36 and PBY straight to the tier 5 F-86-A5 and the B-57B. At the time, those were the end-game planes for the US (B-57B is still the last American jet bomber as of this draft). People have worked for literal years to achieve what I did in just 5 minutes. The only thing that'd stop players from abusing this like crazy is the pricetag for Eagles; $115 CDN for the maximum amount. Eagles can also purchase a limited-time 'premium' membership for up to a year which pretty much doubles your rewards for every game. This point isn't so dramatic since every MMO seems to do this now, but it further cements the ball in P2W's court. Eagles can also be used to purchase 'Premium\" vehicles with a permenant reward boost, fortunately most aren't very good for very long. And my f-ing God is this a massive grind fest! It will literally take you 12 hours a day for about a year of non-stop grinding to reach the first tier of jet aircraft, moreso for tanks. It's beyond stupid. Grinding is a chore, people don't play games to do chores. Why are we expected to play the game for years before we get the results we want? Answer: It incentivizes us to throw our money at Gaijin for a shortcut. Layman's terms: Gaijin is pushing us to spend money on their game by making it grindy AF. The maps can be very annoying as well, especially when it spawns at night. Most are asymemstical, which gives one team a distinct advantage over the other, usually by giving them easier access to objectives, choke points to force the other team through, more cover, higher ground, etc. As mentioned before maps have time of day settings, which means there's a chance of having a night fight, where you can barely see the landscape 3 meters away, let alone an enemy player. Which brings up a glaring exploit: graphics. I understand Gaijin's desire for everyone regardless of whether or not they have a decent gaming PC to enjoy their game, but when someone can simply lower the terrain graphics to their lowest setting to cheat and literally render all distant bushes invisible so they can see me wherever I am, there's a major issue, one that probably cannot/ will not be solved. Honestly, I really could go on with all the problems in War Thunder and in continued honesty, there's not a whole lot good about it. The module damage/crew knockout system was a good concept but grew frustrating (how many f-ing times do we need to get killed by \"pilot knocked out\"?!), there's a decent selection of not-very-balanced war machines with more being added every 4 - 6 months, custom battles can be fun with friends, and it's good if you need to kill time or get yourself frustrated for whatever reason. Beyond that, those are the good things I can remember about the game off the top of my head. Since this review is getting rather long and I doubt people are actually going to read the whole bloody thing, I'm cutting it off here. Did I miss anything? Feel I didn't go into something more than I should have? I get something wrong? Feel free to comment and let me know! As always, please be respectful, on-topic, and if you're going to dispute anything within this review please keep it professional. Anything along the lines of \"u haIt my favrite gaem!!1! I HAIT U!!!\" or trolling/flaming in general will be removed. I don't have time for your pettiness and neither do the people who actually use the reviews/comments section properly. Edits: spelling, grammar, added section about grinding", "appid": "236390", "steamid": "profiles/76561198051469629", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "7", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1524744000.0}
