{"text": "I can't recommend this given the other great cars in this game, for its flawed hit box alone. This car has pros and cons, and if the hitbox is brought in line I'd be happy to recommend it. Pros: Gorgeous - This car looks and sounds amazing. Many decals look great on it. The old-school long car look is a real pleasure. The low throaty idle sound is perfect. The sound at full throttle is a little lacking but still great. Many decals look great on this car, including Black Markets that really accentuate the lines of the car. Unique Handling - This car has the same hit box as the Dominus but its pivot points are noticably rearward, giving the car a certain rear weight that is unique and sets it apart. The car has a boaty feel to it that befits its appearance. I'm not entirely sure what all of the handling variables imply, but this car changes how flicks, jumps, and aerials feel. Con: Hitbox - The hitbox for this car (Dominus) does not fit the model which is noticeably longer, and less wide. People can argue about why, but if I'm using a car I want the car I see to behave like the car the game engine sees, and right now this is not the case.  The front of the car has a small clipping, but this is actually seen on a few other models and while it looks ugly if you plant your nose into the ground, it won't actually lead to very many/different shots for most people.  The box for the top of the car extends well over the top of the car, which is a bit noticeable while dribbling, but the height is in line with other game cars so the dribbling feels familiar, even though it looks off. Actually a number of cars have this top-of-car-box issue, including the other Dominus cars. The box on the back of the car is inexcusably inaccurate, and ruins a lot of redirects and flicks that bamboozle you with a clip through a ball. In fact, this is the only reason that I can't recommend the car, and if the back hit box is ever brought into line with the model, then I'd happily thumbs it as another great car in my garage. There are claims of \"balance issues\" with making the hit box fit the model, which I find odd for two reasons. First, I've never felt I lost a game due to another player using  an octane or a batmobile. I would propose a new hitbox that would be the longest in the game, but would be significantly less wide and less tall to fit the model. This may cause balance issues, but I don't see much reason for it, and if it does there are other stats that can nerfed to bring the competitive level into line. For example the turning radius of this car under normal acceleration, boost, or e-brake could all be reduced to exaggerate the already boaty feel of this car.", "appid": "457192", "steamid": "profiles/76561198066552374", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": "17", "votes_funny": "1", "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1492084800.0}
